  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA205-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">1. itu talaimakaṉ taṉṉeñciṟkuc collic celavu aḻuṅkiyatu.
            2. tōḻi celavu aḻuṅkac colliyatūumām.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">1. This is how HE prevented going, speaking to his own heart.
            2. It is also how the confidante prevented going.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA205">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            aruvi yārkkum peruvarai yaṭukkat</l>
<l>            tāḷi naṉmāṉ vēṭṭeḻu kōḷukirp</l>
<l>            pūmpoṟi yuḻuvai tolaicciya vainnuti</l>
<l>            yēntuveṇ kōṭṭu vayakaḷi ṟiḻukkun</l>
<l>            tuṉṉaruṅ kāṉa meṉṉāy nīyē </l>
<l>            kuvaḷai yuṇka ṇivaḷīṇ ṭoḻiya</l>
<l>            vāḷviṉaik kakaṟi yāyi ṉiṉṟoṭu</l>
<l>            pōyiṉṟu kollō tāṉē paṭappaik</l>
<l>            koṭumu ḷīṅkai neṭumā vantaḷir</l>
<l>            nīrmali kataḻpeya ṟalaiiya </l>
<l>            vāyniṟam puraiyumivaṇ māmaik kaviṉē.</l>
        </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O you who do not say that the forest is difficult to approach,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the good bull(?) of the Āḷi<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">Āḷi</term> is, alas, another of these fabulous beasts. Here the context is too thin by far, but judging also from other descriptions, especially in the Akanāṉūṟu, it seems to be carnivorous and dangerous, feared by elephants and tigers (cf. AN 78.1, 252.2, 381.1).</note> drags along the strong elephant bull</l>
<l rend="indent2">with raised white tusks with sharp tips that had destroyed</l>
<l rend="indent3">the flower-dotted(?)<note place="foot">Does not this rather point to a leopard? Are/were there leopard in the area?</note> tiger with murderous nails on the rise for a hunt</l>
<l rend="indent3">on the side of the big mountain where waterfalls roar,</l>
<l rend="indent">– if you were to depart to [your] manly work</l>
<l rend="indent4">for her with waterlily collyrium eyes to stay behind,</l>
<l>would it not be gone with the very day,</l>
<l>her dark beauty that is like the choice colour,</l>
<l rend="indent2">that has been offered quick rain, abounding in water,<note place="foot">Actually we would want line 10 to precede line 9, since it is not the colour that has had rain, but the sprout.</note></l>
<l rend="indent4">of the long dark pretty sprouts of the mimosa with curved thorns?</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="2-4b">
<l>    where the strong elephant bull drags himself along, with raised</l>
<l> 	white tusks with sharp tips that had destroyed the flower-dotted</l>
<l> 	tiger with murderous nail on the rise for a hunt on the good deer of</l>
<l> 	Āḷi.<note place="foot">These are just two ways of construing this typically unmarked inset. Actually most commentaries will have it that the tiger drags the elephant. T.V.G. prefers version a.</note></l>
</lg>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="7+8b">
<l>    – when you depart for [your] manly work,</l>
<l>    it is gone with the very day<note place="foot">Problematic here is the <term xml:lang="ta">pōyiṉṟu kollō</term>. This particle usually marks strongly emotional and rhetorical questions, and as such we would expect a negation: would it not be gone? Now this works out fine if we concede that <term xml:lang="ta">pōyiṉṟu</term> can be analysed as a negative form (<term xml:lang="ta">pō-y-il-tu</term>). This is contrary to the grammatical tradition that allows only <term xml:lang="ta">al</term> as infix (see, however, KT 114.4 <term xml:lang="ta">pōkiṉṟu</term>, which also is best taken as a negative). T.V.G. solution to the problem is version b: an emphatic statement.</note></l>
</lg>
        </lg>
      </div>
